hands_on_practices.solution:
1. Disk temperature from local energy balance $2\sigma T^4 = D(r) = \frac{3GM\dot M}{4\pi r^3}\Bigl[1-\sqrt{\frac{R_*}{r}}\Bigr]$:
   $$T(r)^4=\frac{3GM\dot M}{8\pi\sigma\,r^3}\Bigl[1-\sqrt{\tfrac{R_*}{r}}\Bigr].$$
2. Introduce $x=r/R_*$. To find the maximum, we maximize $g(x)=x^{-3}(1-x^{-1/2})$.
   $$\frac{dg}{dx}=-3x^{-4}+\frac{7}{2}x^{-9/2}=0
     \;\Longrightarrow\;x^{1/2}=\frac{7}{6}.$$
   This gives $r_{\max}=\frac{49}{36}R_*$. At this radius, $\sqrt{R_*/r_{\max}} = 6/7$.
3. Maximum disk temperature:
   $$T_{\max}^4
     =\frac{3GM\dot M}{8\pi\sigma\,(r_{\max})^3}\Bigl(1-\tfrac{6}{7}\Bigr)
     =\frac{3GM\dot M}{8\pi\sigma R_*^3}\frac{36^3}{49^3}\frac{1}{7}
     =\frac{17496}{823543}\frac{GM\dot M}{\pi\sigma R_*^3}.$$
4. Boundary‐layer luminosity and temperature:
   $$L_{BL}=\frac{GM\dot M}{2R_*}
     =2\pi\,(r_{\max}^2-R_*^2)\,\sigma\,T_{BL}^4
     \;\Longrightarrow\;
     T_{BL}^4=\frac{GM\dot M}{4\pi\sigma R_*(r_{\max}^2-R_*^2)}$$
   With $r_{\max}^2-R_*^2=R_*^2(49^2/36^2-1)=R_*^2(1105/1296)$, this becomes:
   $$T_{BL}^4
     =\frac{324}{1105}\frac{GM\dot M}{\pi\sigma R_*^3}.$$
5. Ratio of temperatures:
   $$\frac{T_{BL}^4}{T_{\max}^4}
     =\frac{\tfrac{324}{1105}}{\tfrac{17496}{823543}}
     =\frac{823543}{59670}
     \;\Longrightarrow\;
     \frac{T_{BL}}{T_{\max}}
     =\Bigl(\frac{823543}{59670}\Bigr)^{\!1/4}.$$
